03906nam a22006615i 9781501743344DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017433447 a10.7591/97815017433442doi  a(DE-B1597)534164  a(OCoLC)1129204186  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0041502bisacsh1 aShiner, Larry E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Secret Mirror :bLiterary Form and History in Tocqueville's "Recollections'' /cLarry E. Shiner. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1988  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCHRONOLOGY OF 1848 -- t1. RHETORIC, READING, AND HISTORY -- t2. GENRE -- t3. PLOT -- t4. CODE -- t5. VOICE -- t6. REFERENCE -- t7. AUTHORSHIP -- t8. LITERATURE AND TRUTH -- tAPPENDIX -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTocqueville opens the Recollections, his deeply ambivalent memoir of the failed 1848 Revolution in France, with an explicit denial of any literary intent or rhetorical appeal. Forced by illness into an unaccustomed state of leisure, Tocqueville claims to record his experiences solely for his own amusement, holding up a "secret mirror" through which he will be able to contemplate the past truthfully. In this innovative study, L. E. Shiner examines the Recollections as a test case of the relation between form and content in historical writing. Drawing on current literary theory and semiotics, Shiner offers a close reading which at once confirms the inevitably literary character of historical writing and demonstrates how rhetorical analysis of Tocqueville's writings deepens our understanding of his political thought.Using the methods of reader-response and rhetorical criticisms, among others, Shiner first analyzes the component genres and narrative structures of the Recollections, the recurring pictorial and thematic codes, and the various voices Tocqueville employs. He then confronts the issue of the truth of Tocqueville's treatment of 1848, in part by comparing it with other key texts on these same events-Marx's The Class Struggles in France and Flaubert's Sentimental Education. Finally, Shiner pursues questions of authorial style, tracing the use of some of the rhetorical devices discussed in the Recollections through Tocqueville's Democracy in America, The Old Regime and the French Revolution, and "A Fortnight in the Wilderness."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 4aHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501743344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501743344.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG